# Domain Mappings Configuration
# =============================
#
# This file maps user email domains to secondary DNS domains for multi-domain
# forward zone generation. Place this file on both primary and secondary servers
# (the sync scripts will handle copying it automatically).
#
# Location: /root/domain_mappings.conf (on production servers)
#
# Format:
#   email_domain:secondary_dns_domain
#
# Rules:
#   - One mapping per line
#   - Lines starting with '#' are comments
#   - Empty lines are ignored
#   - Whitespace around ':' is trimmed
#   - Email domain matching is case-insensitive
#
# How it works:
#   - Every hostname ALWAYS gets a forward zone with the primary domain (--domain)
#   - If ANY user associated with a hostname has an email matching a mapped
#     email domain, an ADDITIONAL forward zone is generated with the secondary domain
#   - One hostname can match multiple mappings if it has users from different domains
#   - If no user matches any mapping, only the primary domain zone is generated
#
# Example scenario:
#   Primary domain: corp.local
#   Mapping: subsidiary.com:subsidiary.local
#
#   Device "LT001" with user "john@subsidiary.com" will get:
#     forward-zone:
#         name: "lt001.corp.local"          <- primary (always generated)
#         forward-addr: 10.0.0.12
#
#     forward-zone:
#         name: "lt001.subsidiary.local"    <- secondary (user matches mapping)
#         forward-addr: 10.0.0.12
#
#   Device "LT002" with user "jane@corp.com" will only get:
#     forward-zone:
#         name: "lt002.corp.local"          <- primary only (no mapping match)
#         forward-addr: 10.0.0.12
#
# Usage:
#   python generate_forward_zones.py devices.csv zones.conf 10.0.0.12 \
#       --domain corp.local --domain-mappings /root/domain_mappings.conf
#

# Add your mappings below:
# subsidiary.com:subsidiary.local
# partner.it:partner.internal
